  "opinion": "The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers—it's about the stories we tell ourselves and the systems we build. As a genderqueer person who's spent most of my life navigating a world that often doesn't fit neatly into boxes, I've seen how science education can either open doors or close them. Growing up in a community where my parents' educational backgrounds were limited, I learned early that success in science wasn't about innate talent but about access and encouragement. Today, as a delivery driver in Washington DC, I see how the lack of role models in STEM fields affects young people who don't see themselves reflected in those spaces. The gap isn't just about women being underrepresented—it's about the ways systems fail to support people who don't fit traditional gender binaries. We need to address this by creating inclusive learning environments that don't assume a single path to scientific success. For example, community-based science programs that bring hands-on projects to neighborhoods where kids might not have access to labs or advanced courses could help. It's not about changing the science itself but about making sure everyone has a chance to contribute. The key is to listen to those who've been marginalized and build systems that honor their experiences. As someone who values both community and practical problem-solving, I believe this work starts with small, local efforts—like partnering with schools to offer science workshops that focus on real-world applications rather than abstract theories. We must remember that science belongs to all of us, not just those who fit the mold.",
